    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="182"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d182">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW 1939/4–1044</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Joint Chiefs of Staff</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-10">10 April
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: Reference is made to the
                    memorandum of Mr. James C. Dunn of April 8, 1944,<note n="55" xml:id="d182fn1"
                        >Not printed.</note> transmitting the terms proposed by the Soviet
                    Government for a Rumanian armistice.</p>
                <p>The Joint Chiefs of Staff are of the opinion that our Government should give its
                    full assent to the military provisions of the proposed terms, the acceptance of
                    which by Rumania would result in the assumption by that nation of a
                    co-belligerent status with the Allies. <pb facs="0182" n="172" xml:id="pg_172"/>
                    Such action by Rumania would be an event of such cardinal importance in the
                    further prosecution of the war that it is hoped that our Government may find a
                    basis for agreement with the Soviet and British Governments on any nonmilitary
                    provisions of the proposed terms.<note n="56" xml:id="d182fn2">In telegram 3469,
                        April 29, 10 p.m., to London, the Department stated that the revised views
                        of the Joint Chiefs of Staff as set forth in Eacom 16, Department’s 2815 of
                        April 10, 6 p.m. (<ref target="frus1944v01#pg_210">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps"
                                >i</hi>, p. 210</ref>), should be taken into account as applying
                        also to surrender terms for the satellite states (740.00119
                        EAC/184a).</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Joint Chiefs of Staff: <lb/>
                    <signed>G. C. <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chief of Staff, U.S. Army</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
